{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"# plan-review container fan-out (G3/G4): token + wall-clock optimization (fidelity-preserving)\n\n## Reproduction Steps\n1. `rebar review-plan <epic>` on an epic with N children (observed N=8).\n2. Review runs >25 min with no completion (appears hung).\n\n## Expected vs Actual\n- Expected: epic review completes in minutes at reasonable token cost.\n- Actual: container criteria G3/G4 run as `2*N` SEQUENTIAL agentic LLM calls (~75-150s each;\n  N=8 ⇒ 16 calls ≈ 27 min). Each call re-sends the WHOLE parent plan + sibling roster, and G3/G4\n  send the same (parent,child) context twice — large token waste on top of the latency.\n\n## Root cause + provenance (PROVEN)\n- `pass1.py:_run_container` runs `for crit in [G3,G4]: for child in children: pass1_container(...)`\n  SEQUENTIALLY, OUTSIDE the ThreadPoolExecutor that parallelizes every other tier. Each pairing is\n  agentic (request_limit≈13). Proven via faulthandler stacks (blocked on network, not spinning) +\n  per-pairing instrumentation (pairings complete and advance at 73-146s each) ⇒ bounded-but-slow, not\n  a loop.\n- NOT a workflow-migration regression. The pairwise split was authored in the BESPOKE harness at\n  commit 832b3af0 (story ca03 / dry-frost-zenith, \"ca03 AC5\", 2026-06-23) — its rationale is\n  CONTEXT-WINDOW FITTING while keeping content whole: \"NO TRUNCATION BY DESIGN, NEVER CHUNK TICKET\n  CONTENT … the lever to fit context is … (for container criteria) the per-child pairing — never the\n  content.\" The workflow migration (ba379b75/8b888716) extracted it verbatim.\n- It is NOT a partial-re-review/changed-children mechanism: the container loop has ZERO\n  checkpoint/resume/scoping (checkpointing lives only in the pool-chunk path); the delta-re-review\n  feature (boil-golem-veto / grace-thud-feint) is separate, later, and explicitly REJECTED subset-reuse\n  as unsound (it uses a tripwire probe → full-re-review escalation).\n- Insight: G3 (child-coverage) and G4 (child-consistency) are inherently CROSS-CHILD criteria; the\n  per-child slice was a window concession that WEAKENS cross-child analysis (one child + a roster of\n  titles, vs whole children seen together). So batching whole children where the window allows can\n  IMPROVE fidelity on these criteria, not merely cut cost.\n\n## Plan (four composable optimizations; all preserve ca03's \"content always whole\" guarantee)\n\n1. **Merge G3 + G4 into one call per bin.** Same (parent, children, roster) context; disjoint audits\n   (coverage vs consistency) the container prompt already describes together. One call evaluates both ⇒\n   2N → N calls. Output must keep per-criterion attribution (findings tagged G3 vs G4). Validate via\n   offline eval (two rubrics in one turn must not dilute either).\n\n2. **Child bin-packing (analogous to the facet criteria batcher).** Pack multiple SMALL whole children\n   into one call (parent + several whole children) up to a token budget = model-window × P8_HEADROOM −\n   output reserve (reuse the existing `pair_tokens`/`budget` machinery + P8 reviewability floor). PRESERVE\n   the single-child path when parent+child strains the window; a child that alone exceeds budget stays the\n   existing \"too-big → reduce the ticket\" failure finding. Each child stays WHOLE (honors \"never chunk\n   content\"). Mitigate per-child attention with structured per-child sections + REQUIRED per-child output.\n   Bonus: improves G4 cross-child consistency (children seen together). Validate via offline eval.\n\n3. **Parallelize for wall-clock.** Submit the (now fewer) merged+batched bins into the existing\n   ThreadPoolExecutor instead of the sequential loop. Also fix the budget cap that scales UP with child\n   count (`sizing.py` centrality `base*(1+centrality)`) so shedding engages for large epics instead of\n   being disabled by the very signal (more children) that should trigger it.\n\n4. **Prompt caching (CONFIRMED feasible + provider-safe).** Insert `pydantic_ai.CachePoint` (pydantic-ai\n   1.107.0) into the user-message content list at the runner seam (`runner.py` ~209/226): stable prefix\n   (system prompt + WHOLE parent plan) first, `CachePoint(ttl=\"5m\")`, volatile suffix (criterion/child)\n   last. On `anthropic:` it caches tools+system+parent-plan (read ≈0.1×); on `openai:`/`google-gla:`/\n   `mistral:` it is SILENTLY FILTERED (no error, no gating needed — pydantic-ai contract). Fidelity-NEUTRAL\n   (identical inputs/outputs). Invariants: prefix must be byte-identical (no per-call dates/UUIDs/unsorted\n   JSON) and clear the model minimum (4096 tokens on Opus 4.8); never make CachePoint the first content\n   block. Biggest single token win because the parent plan is re-sent across every bin/call.\n\nCombined for an 8-child epic: ~16 calls → a handful of parallel merged+batched calls with the parent plan\nbilled once and read cheaply — token cost and wall-clock both down, fidelity preserved or improved.\n\n## Sequencing (risk-ordered)\n- (4) caching first — fidelity-neutral, no behavior change, biggest win, lowest risk.\n- (3) parallelize + budget-cap fix — wall-clock; no fidelity change.\n- (1) merge G3+G4 — behind an offline eval.\n- (2) child bin-packing — behind an offline eval; preserve single-child fallback; required per-child output.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Caching: a `CachePoint` is inserted at the runner seam; on Anthropic, `usage.cache_read_input_tokens`\n      is non-zero on repeat calls sharing the prefix; on OpenAI/Gemini the call still succeeds unchanged\n      (provider-safe); the cached prefix is byte-stable (no per-call interpolation).\n- [ ] Merge: G3 and G4 are evaluated in ONE call per bin with findings correctly attributed to each; an\n      offline eval shows no accuracy regression vs separate calls.\n- [ ] Bin-packing: small children are packed up to the window budget; a child whose (parent+child) strains\n      the window keeps its own call; each child is whole (never chunked); per-child output is required; an\n      offline eval shows no per-child attention loss.\n- [ ] Parallel: bins run concurrently in the thread pool; the budget cap no longer disables shedding as\n      child count grows.\n- [ ] Measured: an 8-child epic review completes in minutes with materially lower token cost; findings are\n      within eval tolerance of the current per-child behavior.\n- [ ] `make lint` + the full test suite pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782540623106083001,"uuid":"b589cefc-1fc7-45e2-9dcd-87c3e58e1f94"}